			'<h5>Prerequisites</h5><p class=\'text-body\'>A very good knowledge of French for texts to be red in the original\nLanguage. Passes in the exams of French Language III and of French\nLiterature III.\n</p><h5>Educational goals</h5><p class=\'text-body\'>MOD.1 LM I A:\nAt the end of the course, the student will have acquired the ability to\nanalyze 16th and 20th French novels from a\nlinguistic and historical-cultural point of view, he will have developed\nadequate critical and comparative capacities of understanding literary\nevents and he will be able to identify their real stylistic, poetical and\nepistemological value in the history of literature and criticism.\nMOD.2 LM I B:\nAt the end of the course, the student will have acquired the ability to\nanalyze 17th and 20th century French theatre  from a linguistic and\nhistorical-cultural point of view, he will have developed adequate critical\nand comparative capacities of understanding literary events and he will\nbe able to identify their real stylistic, poetical and epistemological value\nin the history of literature and criticism.\n</p><h5>Course content</h5><p class=\'text-body\'>MOD. 1 LM I A:\n"War\'s Images and Grotesque between 16th and 20th French Century: Rabelais, Cendrars and C\u00e9line".\nThrough the study of Fran\u00e7ois Rabelais "Gargantua" (1534) novel, of Blaise Cendrars "La main coup\u00e9e" (1946) novel and ""J\'ai tu\u00e9, suivi de J\'ai saign\u00e9" (2023, posthumous) prose, and also of Louis-Ferdinand C\u00e9line\'s "Guerre" novel (2022, posthumous), , the student will address\nthe originality of the grotesque body in French Renaissance, the denunciation of war\'s absurdity and the stylistical and linguistical innovation of two of the most important French writers of the 20th century.\nMOD. 2 LM I B:\n"French Theatre between 17th and 20th Century: Corneille, Moli\u00e8re and Kolt\u00e8s".\nThrough the study of Pierre Corneille\'s tragic comedy "Le Cid" (1637), of the Moli\u00e8re\'s comedy-ballet "Le Malade imaginaire" (1673), and  of the Bernard-Marie Kolt\u00e8s\' pi\u00e8ce "La Marche" (2003), the student will learn the most important stylistical characteristics of "classical" French theatre, and their poetical contemporary evolution.\nContents will also be discussed in a teaching perspective, so as to provide\nopportunities for further analyses.\n</p><h5>Teaching methods</h5><p class=\'text-body\'>Lectures in French, with some parts of the program\'s texts orally\nanalyzed and translated by the students with the teacher during the\ncourse.\n</p><h5>Assessment and Evaluation</h5><p class=\'text-body\'>The examination is oral. Reading, translation (a required ability to\ncontinue the examination) and comment on literary extracts from course\ntexts, in order to test the linguistic, literary and specially critical\ncompetences of the students. The examination consists in three or four\nopen questions for every module concerning literary and critical texts in\nthe syllabus, in order to test the acquisition of the program\'s goals, and\nthe quality of expression.\n</p><h5>Further information</h5><p class=\'text-body\'>ERASMUS students will not be asked to translate French authors texts\ninto italian during the oral exam, but they have to prepare the complete\nbibliography of the course in all its French and Italian parts.\nStudents are kindly invited to see the list of texts to be red and studied,\nwhich are a basic part of the program, on the application Leganto.\nThe modalities of the course and of the examinations described by the\nsyllabus could be changed because of the authorities decisions in case of\na new eventual epidemiological emergency.\nTexts to be red:\nFran\u00e7ois Rabelais, "Gargantua", in Lionello Sozzi (a cura di), "Gargantua e Pantagruele", "Classici della Letteratura Europea", Bompiani, Milano, 2012/2013, capp.: "Aux lecteurs", "Prologue", VI, VII, XI, XXI, XXIII,  XXV, XXVI, XXVIII, XXIX, XXX, XXXI, XXXII, LII, LIII.\nBlaise Cendrars, "La main coup\u00e9e",  Folio Denoel, Paris, 2022.\nBlaise Cendrars, "J\'ai tu\u00e9, suivi de J\'ai saign\u00e9", Zoe Poche, Gen\u00e8ve, 2023.\nLouis-Ferdinand C\u00e9line, "Guerre", \u00e9d. \u00e9tablie par Pascal Fouch\u00e9, avant-propos de Fran\u00e7ois Gibault, Gallimard, Paris, 2022 (trad. it. : "Guerra", Adelphi, Milano, 2023).\nMoli\u00e8re, "Le Malade imaginaire", \u00e9d. de Georges Couton, Folio Classique, Gallimard, Paris, 2020.\nPierre Corneille "Il Cid", \u00e9d. di Luigi Lunari, trad. di Giancarlo Monti, testo francese a fronte, I Classici, Universale Economica Feltrinelli, Milano, 2012.\nBernard-Marie Kolt\u00e8s, "La marche", Les Editions de Minuit, Paris, 2003.\nEssays to be studied:\nMireille Huchon, "Rabelais", "Biblioteca di Studi Francesi, 16", trad. di Maurizio Busca e Andrea Martina, Rosenberg & Sellier, Torino, 2022.\nHenri Godard, "C\u00e9line", Folio Gallimard, Paris, 2011.\nAndr\u00e9 Petitjean, "Bernard-Marie Kolt\u00e8s. Portrait d\'un dramaturge en \u00e9crivain", Essais EUD, Editions Universitaires de Dijon, 2019.\nMichela Landi, "Letteratura francese. Dalle origini al Seicento", Le Monnier Universit\u00e0, Firenze, Parte Seconda. "Il Cinquecento", Parte Terza. "Il Seicento".\n</p>',
